# Article 3: Artificial Sweeteners and Diet Sodas Increase Body Fat

## Translated Title
Artificial Sweeteners and Diet Sodas Increase Body Fat

## Category
P1 — Nutrition, Metabolism, Obesity

## Source Study
- **International Journal of Obesity** (2023) — CARDIA Study

## Key Findings

### Study Design
- **25-year CARDIA longitudinal study**
- n=3,088 adults
- CT-measured adipose tissue (visceral, intermuscular, subcutaneous)

### Key Results
- Long-term aspartame intake → increased visceral adipose tissue
- Long-term saccharin intake → increased intermuscular adipose tissue
- Diet soda consumption → increased subcutaneous adipose tissue
- Effects **independent of total caloric intake and diet quality**
- Higher artificial sweetener intake → increased obesity risk over time

### Clinical Implications
- Current public health recommendations to replace sugar with artificial sweeteners may need re-evaluation
- Both sugar and artificial sweeteners may have negative health impacts
- Whole, unprocessed foods remain the safest choice

### Recommended Foods
- Red meat, eggs, fermented dairy, fish, seafood
- Olives, olive oil, vegetables, fruits
- Honey, nuts, legumes
- Reduce grains, flours, baked goods

## Key References
- [[Steffen_2023_CARDIA_Artificial_Sweeteners_R-002-0003]] — Primary study

## Extraction Status
- [x] SPARK check: Artificial sweetener zettels exist; fat distribution findings are NEW
- [x] Priority: P1 (important metabolic finding, challenges conventional advice)
